Js: numbers

let num = 1.5;
let num = 10;

-It is accurate up to 15-16 digits 
-BigInteger data type is used for larger numbers 

"2" * 5 => 10
"10" / "2" => 5
"abc" * "Hello"     => NaN (Not a Number) //Trying to do arithmetic with a non-numeric string 
                                            will result in NaN (Not a Number).


Number functions
toPrecision(2) -> you want to see 2 digits regardless of decimal point
toFixed(2) -> you want to see 2 digits for the decimal point

isInteger() vs isSafeInteger() :

Example:                                Integer                                 Safe Integer
25                                      true                                    true
753289458684568347590275918539202348    true                                    false

-9007199254740991 to 9007199254740991 -> any number between these is a safe integer and can be stored as a number
Anything less than  -9007199254740991 or more than 9007199254740991 

JavaScript Math Object Functions
-abs(x) - returns the absolute value of x
-ceil(x) - returns x, rounded upwards to the nearest integer
-floor(x) - returns x, rounded downwards to the nearest integer
-max(x1,x2,..) - returns the number with the highest value
-min(x1,x2,..) - returns the number with the lowest value
-pow(x, y) - returns the value of x to the power of y
-random() - returns a random number between 0 and 1 (0 included but 1 excluded)
-round(x) - rounds x to the nearest integer
-sqrt(x) - returns the square root of x
-trunc(x) - returns the integer part of a number (x)
